McKinsey is continuing to reckon with its role in the opioid crisis, with the consulting giant announcing on Wednesday that its global managing partner, Kevin Sneader, would leave the firm. Sneader&#39;s departure,  which stemmed from a vote of 600 senior partners, follows McKinsey&#39;s $574 million legal battle to settle claims that its advice had &#34;exacerbated the deadly US opioid crisis.&#34; The firm counseled Purdue Pharma, the maker of the painkiller OxyContin, on the payment of “rebates” to drugstores predicated on the number of people who  died or became addicted after using the drug.
  During Sneader&#39;s &#34;tumultuous tenure&#34;, the firm has dealt with controversies related to its work in Saudi Arabia and South Africa, where it eventually returned &#34;tens of millions of dollars in fees,&#34;  The New York Times reports.
 McKinsey has also been involved in a recent controversy for  its work with the French government in connection with the rollout of the coronavirus vaccine, which was &#34;derided for being far too slow.&#34;
